{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HH91cxTzvX46ntKK8ycnH9","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t{\n2\t  \"overview\": \"A two-tier leave management system consisting of a React-based frontend (leave-web-app) for employees and managers to submit, view, and manage leave requests, and a Go backend service (leave-api) that handles business logic, leave balance calculations, approval workflows, and data persistence. Communication occurs via RESTful HTTP between the web app and the API service.\",\n3\t  \"requirements\": [\n4\t    \"Employees must be able to submit leave requests specifying start date, end date, leave type, and reason\",\n5\t    \"Managers must be able to view all pending leave requests from their direct reports\",\n6\t    \"Managers must be able to approve or reject leave requests with optional comments\",\n7\t    \"Employees must be able to view their remaining leave balance segmented by leave type (e.g., annual, sick, personal)\",\n8\t    \"All users must be able to view the history and current status of their own leave requests\",\n9\t    \"The system must validate that leave requests do not exceed available balance before submission\",\n10\t    \"The system must prevent overlapping leave requests for the same employee\",\n11\t    \"The API must expose a health check endpoint for Kubernetes liveness and readiness probes\",\n12\t    \"The frontend must provide a responsive user interface accessible from desktop and mobile browsers\",\n13\t    \"Manager-employee relationships must be maintained to enforce approval workflows\",\n14\t    \"Leave request statuses must include at least: pending, approved, rejected\",\n15\t    \"The system must record timestamps for all state transitions (submitted, approved, rejected)\"\n16\t  ],\n17\t  \"components\": [\n18\t    {\n19\t      \"name\": \"leave-web-app\",\n20\t      \"componentType\": \"web-app\",\n21\t      \"language\": \"TypeScript / React\",\n22\t      \"dependsOn\": [\n23\t        \"leave-api\"\n24\t      ],\n25\t      \"entrypoint\": \"deployment/web-application\",\n26\t      \"buildpack\": \"docker\",\n27\t      \"appPath\": \"/leave-web-app\",\n28\t      \"openAPISpec\": \"openapi: 3.0.3\\ninfo:\\n  title: Leave Web Application\\n  version: 1.0.0\\n  description: Frontend SPA for leave management system\\npaths:\\n  /health:\\n    get:\\n      summary: Health check endpoint\\n      responses:\\n        '200':\\n          description: Application is healthy\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                type: object\\n                properties:\\n                  status:\\n                    type: string\\n                    example: ok\",\n29\t      \"componentAgentInstructions\": \"Implement a TypeScript React single-page application (SPA) for leave management. Use Create React App or Vite as the build tool. The application serves on port 3000 inside the container. Implement the following routes and features: (1) /login - simple login form that captures employeeId and role (employee or manager), stores in localStorage or context. (2) /dashboard - shows different views based on role: for employees display leave balance by type, button to request new leave, and list of their own requests with status; for managers display pending requests from direct reports with approve/reject buttons. (3) /request - form to submit new leave request with fields: leaveType (dropdown: annual, sick, personal), startDate, endDate, reason (textarea). Validate dates and call POST /api/leave-requests on leave-api. (4) /history - table showing all leave requests for the logged-in user with columns: dates, type, reason, status, manager comments. All API calls go to the leave-api service via relative path /api/* (configure proxy or environment variable for base URL). Display loading states and error messages for failed API calls. Use React Router for navigation. Style with a component library like Material-UI or Ant Design. Include a /health endpoint that returns {status: 'ok'}. Build a production Docker image using multi-stage build: node:18 for build, nginx:alpine for serving static files. Configure nginx to serve index.html for all routes (SPA routing). Handle 401/403 responses by redirecting to login. Show manager comments when a request is approved or rejected. Prevent submission if employee has insufficient balance (call GET /api/employees/{id}/balance first). Display user-friendly error messages for validation failures.\"\n30\t    },\n31\t    {\n32\t      \"name\": \"leave-api\",\n33\t      \"componentType\": \"service\",\n34\t      \"language\": \"Go\",\n35\t      \"dependsOn\": [],\n36\t      \"entrypoint\": \"deployment/service\",\n37\t      \"buildpack\": \"docker\",\n38\t      \"appPath\": \"/leave-api\",\n39\t      \"openAPISpec\": \"openapi: 3.0.3\\ninfo:\\n  title: Leave Management API\\n  version: 1.0.0\\n  description: Backend service for managing employee leave requests and approvals\\nservers:\\n  - url: http://localhost:9090\\npaths:\\n  /health:\\n    get:\\n      summary: Health check endpoint\\n      operationId: healthCheck\\n      responses:\\n        '200':\\n          description: Service is healthy\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                type: object\\n                properties:\\n                  status:\\n                    type: string\\n                    example: ok\\n  /api/leave-requests:\\n    post:\\n      summary: Submit a new leave request\\n      operationId: createLeaveRequest\\n      requestBody:\\n        required: true\\n        content:\\n          application/json:\\n            schema:\\n              type: object\\n              required:\\n                - employeeId\\n                - leaveType\\n                - startDate\\n                - endDate\\n                - reason\\n              properties:\\n                employeeId:\\n                  type: string\\n                leaveType:\\n                  type: string\\n                  enum: [annual, sick, personal]\\n                startDate:\\n                  type: string\\n                  format: date\\n                endDate:\\n                  type: string\\n                  format: date\\n                reason:\\n                  type: string\\n      responses:\\n        '201':\\n          description: Leave request created\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                $ref: '#/components/schemas/LeaveRequest'\\n        '400':\\n          description: Invalid request or insufficient balance\\n        '409':\\n          description: Overlapping leave request exists\\n    get:\\n      summary: Get leave requests (filtered by employeeId or managerId)\\n      operationId: listLeaveRequests\\n      parameters:\\n        - name: employeeId\\n          in: query\\n          schema:\\n            type: string\\n        - name: managerId\\n          in: query\\n          schema:\\n            type: string\\n        - name: status\\n          in: query\\n          schema:\\n            type: string\\n            enum: [pending, approved, rejected]\\n      responses:\\n        '200':\\n          description: List of leave requests\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                type: array\\n                items:\\n                  $ref: '#/components/schemas/LeaveRequest'\\n  /api/leave-requests/{id}/approve:\\n    post:\\n      summary: Approve a leave request\\n      operationId: approveLeaveRequest\\n      parameters:\\n        - name: id\\n          in: path\\n          required: true\\n          schema:\\n            type: string\\n      requestBody:\\n        content:\\n          application/json:\\n            schema:\\n              type: object\\n              required:\\n                - managerId\\n              properties:\\n                managerId:\\n                  type: string\\n                comments:\\n                  type: string\\n      responses:\\n        '200':\\n          description: Leave request approved\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                $ref: '#/components/schemas/LeaveRequest'\\n        '403':\\n          description: Manager not authorized to approve this request\\n        '404':\\n          description: Leave request not found\\n  /api/leave-requests/{id}/reject:\\n    post:\\n      summary: Reject a leave request\\n      operationId: rejectLeaveRequest\\n      parameters:\\n        - name: id\\n          in: path\\n          required: true\\n          schema:\\n            type: string\\n      requestBody:\\n        content:\\n          application/json:\\n            schema:\\n              type: object\\n              required:\\n                - managerId\\n              properties:\\n                managerId:\\n                  type: string\\n                comments:\\n                  type: string\\n      responses:\\n        '200':\\n          description: Leave request rejected\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                $ref: '#/components/schemas/LeaveRequest'\\n        '403':\\n          description: Manager not authorized to reject this request\\n        '404':\\n          description: Leave request not found\\n  /api/employees/{id}/balance:\\n    get:\\n      summary: Get leave balance for an employee\\n      operationId: getLeaveBalance\\n      parameters:\\n        - name: id\\n          in: path\\n          required: true\\n          schema:\\n            type: string\\n      responses:\\n        '200':\\n          description: Leave balance by type\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                type: object\\n                properties:\\n                  employeeId:\\n                    type: string\\n                  balances:\\n                    type: object\\n                    properties:\\n                      annual:\\n                        type: number\\n                        format: float\\n                      sick:\\n                        type: number\\n                        format: float\\n                      personal:\\n                        type: number\\n                        format: float\\n        '404':\\n          description: Employee not found\\ncomponents:\\n  schemas:\\n    LeaveRequest:\\n      type: object\\n      properties:\\n        id:\\n          type: string\\n        employeeId:\\n          type: string\\n        managerId:\\n          type: string\\n        leaveType:\\n          type: string\\n          enum: [annual, sick, personal]\\n        startDate:\\n          type: string\\n          format: date\\n        endDate:\\n          type: string\\n          format: date\\n        reason:\\n          type: string\\n        status:\\n          type: string\\n          enum: [pending, approved, rejected]\\n        managerComments:\\n          type: string\\n        submittedAt:\\n          type: string\\n          format: date-time\\n        reviewedAt:\\n          type: string\\n          format: date-time\",\n40\t      \"componentAgentInstructions\": \"Implement a Go HTTP service using net/http on port 9090. Use the standard library for routing (http.ServeMux) or a lightweight router like gorilla/mux or chi. Store data in-memory using Go maps and structs (no database required for this prototype). Define these structs: Employee (id, name, managerId, leaveBalances map[string]float64), LeaveRequest (id, employeeId, managerId, leaveType, startDate, endDate, reason, status, managerComments, submittedAt, reviewedAt). Initialize sample data: at least 5 employees with 2 managers, each employee has initial balances (annual: 20, sick: 10, personal: 5). Manager-employee relationships must be set via managerId field. Implement these endpoints: (1) GET /health returns {status: 'ok'}. (2) POST /api/leave-requests accepts JSON, validates fields, checks for overlapping requests (same employee, overlapping date range), verifies sufficient balance by calculating business days between dates and comparing to available balance, generates UUID for id, sets status to pending, captures submittedAt timestamp, deducts balance immediately (optimistic), returns 201 with created object or 400/409 on validation failure. (3) GET /api/leave-requests supports query params employeeId, managerId, status; if managerId is provided, return only requests from that manager's direct reports; if employeeId is provided, return that employee's requests; if status is provided, filter by status; return array of LeaveRequest objects. (4) POST /api/leave-requests/{id}/approve accepts managerId and optional comments, verifies the manager is the direct manager of the employee who submitted the request (403 if not), sets status to approved, captures reviewedAt timestamp, stores managerComments, returns updated LeaveRequest. (5) POST /api/leave-requests/{id}/reject accepts managerId and optional comments, verifies manager authorization same as approve, sets status to rejected, restores the deducted leave balance, captures reviewedAt, stores managerComments, returns updated LeaveRequest. (6) GET /api/employees/{id}/balance returns current balances by type for the employee. Use proper HTTP status codes. Enable CORS for frontend access. Use sync.RWMutex for thread-safe access to in-memory data. Parse dates in YYYY-MM-DD format. Calculate business days excluding weekends for balance deduction (simple heuristic: (endDate - startDate + 1) * 5/7). Log requests to stdout. Handle edge cases: invalid date ranges (end before start), non-existent employee or manager IDs (404), attempting to approve already approved/rejected requests (400). Return JSON errors with {error: 'message'} structure. Dockerfile: multi-stage build with golang:1.21 for build and alpine:latest for runtime, expose port 9090, set CMD to run the binary.\"\n41\t    }\n42\t  ],\n43\t  \"sourceSpec\": \"spec-v1\"\n44\t}"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d7e8bf62-199f-4dd8-b4d4-7def9b222e46","uuid":"8160d299-c9dd-420d-a613-7c3e2605d412","timestamp":"2026-04-24T09:03:11.744Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/kajendran/.asdlc/repos/default/kaj-test-17/.asdlc/design.json","content":"{\n  \"overview\": \"A two-tier leave management system consisting of a React-based frontend (leave-web-app) for employees and managers to submit, view, and manage leave requests, and a Go backend service (leave-api) that handles business logic, leave balance calculations, approval workflows, and data persistence. Communication occurs via RESTful HTTP between the web app and the API service.\",\n  \"requirements\": [\n    \"Employees must be able to submit leave requests specifying start date, end date, leave type, and reason\",\n    \"Managers must be able to view all pending leave requests from their direct reports\",\n    \"Managers must be able to approve or reject leave requests with optional comments\",\n    \"Employees must be able to view their remaining leave balance segmented by leave type (e.g., annual, sick, personal)\",\n    \"All users must be able to view the history and current status of their own leave requests\",\n    \"The system must validate that leave requests do not exceed available balance before submission\",\n    \"The system must prevent overlapping leave requests for the same employee\",\n    \"The API must expose a health check endpoint for Kubernetes liveness and readiness probes\",\n    \"The frontend must provide a responsive user interface accessible from desktop and mobile browsers\",\n    \"Manager-employee relationships must be maintained to enforce approval workflows\",\n    \"Leave request statuses must include at least: pending, approved, rejected\",\n    \"The system must record timestamps for all state transitions (submitted, approved, rejected)\"\n  ],\n  \"components\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"leave-web-app\",\n      \"componentType\": \"web-app\",\n      \"language\": \"TypeScript / React\",\n      \"dependsOn\": [\n        \"leave-api\"\n      ],\n      \"entrypoint\": \"deployment/web-application\",\n      \"buildpack\": \"docker\",\n      \"appPath\": \"/leave-web-app\",\n      \"openAPISpec\": \"openapi: 3.0.3\\ninfo:\\n  title: Leave Web Application\\n  version: 1.0.0\\n  description: Frontend SPA for leave management system\\npaths:\\n  /health:\\n    get:\\n      summary: Health check endpoint\\n      responses:\\n        '200':\\n          description: Application is healthy\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                type: object\\n                properties:\\n                  status:\\n                    type: string\\n                    example: ok\",\n      \"componentAgentInstructions\": \"Implement a TypeScript React single-page application (SPA) for leave management. Use Create React App or Vite as the build tool. The application serves on port 3000 inside the container. Implement the following routes and features: (1) /login - simple login form that captures employeeId and role (employee or manager), stores in localStorage or context. (2) /dashboard - shows different views based on role: for employees display leave balance by type, button to request new leave, and list of their own requests with status; for managers display pending requests from direct reports with approve/reject buttons. (3) /request - form to submit new leave request with fields: leaveType (dropdown: annual, sick, personal), startDate, endDate, reason (textarea). Validate dates and call POST /api/leave-requests on leave-api. (4) /history - table showing all leave requests for the logged-in user with columns: dates, type, reason, status, manager comments. All API calls go to the leave-api service via relative path /api/* (configure proxy or environment variable for base URL). Display loading states and error messages for failed API calls. Use React Router for navigation. Style with a component library like Material-UI or Ant Design. Include a /health endpoint that returns {status: 'ok'}. Build a production Docker image using multi-stage build: node:18 for build, nginx:alpine for serving static files. Configure nginx to serve index.html for all routes (SPA routing). Handle 401/403 responses by redirecting to login. Show manager comments when a request is approved or rejected. Prevent submission if employee has insufficient balance (call GET /api/employees/{id}/balance first). Display user-friendly error messages for validation failures.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"leave-api\",\n      \"componentType\": \"service\",\n      \"language\": \"Go\",\n      \"dependsOn\": [],\n      \"entrypoint\": \"deployment/service\",\n      \"buildpack\": \"docker\",\n      \"appPath\": \"/leave-api\",\n      \"openAPISpec\": \"openapi: 3.0.3\\ninfo:\\n  title: Leave Management API\\n  version: 1.0.0\\n  description: Backend service for managing employee leave requests and approvals\\nservers:\\n  - url: http://localhost:9090\\npaths:\\n  /health:\\n    get:\\n      summary: Health check endpoint\\n      operationId: healthCheck\\n      responses:\\n        '200':\\n          description: Service is healthy\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                type: object\\n                properties:\\n                  status:\\n                    type: string\\n                    example: ok\\n  /api/leave-requests:\\n    post:\\n      summary: Submit a new leave request\\n      operationId: createLeaveRequest\\n      requestBody:\\n        required: true\\n        content:\\n          application/json:\\n            schema:\\n              type: object\\n              required:\\n                - employeeId\\n                - leaveType\\n                - startDate\\n                - endDate\\n                - reason\\n              properties:\\n                employeeId:\\n                  type: string\\n                leaveType:\\n                  type: string\\n                  enum: [annual, sick, personal]\\n                startDate:\\n                  type: string\\n                  format: date\\n                endDate:\\n                  type: string\\n                  format: date\\n                reason:\\n                  type: string\\n      responses:\\n        '201':\\n          description: Leave request created\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                $ref: '#/components/schemas/LeaveRequest'\\n        '400':\\n          description: Invalid request or insufficient balance\\n        '409':\\n          description: Overlapping leave request exists\\n    get:\\n      summary: Get leave requests (filtered by employeeId or managerId)\\n      operationId: listLeaveRequests\\n      parameters:\\n        - name: employeeId\\n          in: query\\n          schema:\\n            type: string\\n        - name: managerId\\n          in: query\\n          schema:\\n            type: string\\n        - name: status\\n          in: query\\n          schema:\\n            type: string\\n            enum: [pending, approved, rejected]\\n      responses:\\n        '200':\\n          description: List of leave requests\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                type: array\\n                items:\\n                  $ref: '#/components/schemas/LeaveRequest'\\n  /api/leave-requests/{id}/approve:\\n    post:\\n      summary: Approve a leave request\\n      operationId: approveLeaveRequest\\n      parameters:\\n        - name: id\\n          in: path\\n          required: true\\n          schema:\\n            type: string\\n      requestBody:\\n        content:\\n          application/json:\\n            schema:\\n              type: object\\n              required:\\n                - managerId\\n              properties:\\n                managerId:\\n                  type: string\\n                comments:\\n                  type: string\\n      responses:\\n        '200':\\n          description: Leave request approved\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                $ref: '#/components/schemas/LeaveRequest'\\n        '403':\\n          description: Manager not authorized to approve this request\\n        '404':\\n          description: Leave request not found\\n  /api/leave-requests/{id}/reject:\\n    post:\\n      summary: Reject a leave request\\n      operationId: rejectLeaveRequest\\n      parameters:\\n        - name: id\\n          in: path\\n          required: true\\n          schema:\\n            type: string\\n      requestBody:\\n        content:\\n          application/json:\\n            schema:\\n              type: object\\n              required:\\n                - managerId\\n              properties:\\n                managerId:\\n                  type: string\\n                comments:\\n                  type: string\\n      responses:\\n        '200':\\n          description: Leave request rejected\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                $ref: '#/components/schemas/LeaveRequest'\\n        '403':\\n          description: Manager not authorized to reject this request\\n        '404':\\n          description: Leave request not found\\n  /api/employees/{id}/balance:\\n    get:\\n      summary: Get leave balance for an employee\\n      operationId: getLeaveBalance\\n      parameters:\\n        - name: id\\n          in: path\\n          required: true\\n          schema:\\n            type: string\\n      responses:\\n        '200':\\n          description: Leave balance by type\\n          content:\\n            application/json:\\n              schema:\\n                type: object\\n                properties:\\n                  employeeId:\\n                    type: string\\n                  balances:\\n                    type: object\\n                    properties:\\n                      annual:\\n                        type: number\\n                        format: float\\n                      sick:\\n                        type: number\\n                        format: float\\n                      personal:\\n                        type: number\\n                        format: float\\n        '404':\\n          description: Employee not found\\ncomponents:\\n  schemas:\\n    LeaveRequest:\\n      type: object\\n      properties:\\n        id:\\n          type: string\\n        employeeId:\\n          type: string\\n        managerId:\\n          type: string\\n        leaveType:\\n          type: string\\n          enum: [annual, sick, personal]\\n        startDate:\\n          type: string\\n          format: date\\n        endDate:\\n          type: string\\n          format: date\\n        reason:\\n          type: string\\n        status:\\n          type: string\\n          enum: [pending, approved, rejected]\\n        managerComments:\\n          type: string\\n        submittedAt:\\n          type: string\\n          format: date-time\\n        reviewedAt:\\n          type: string\\n          format: date-time\",\n      \"componentAgentInstructions\": \"Implement a Go HTTP service using net/http on port 9090. Use the standard library for routing (http.ServeMux) or a lightweight router like gorilla/mux or chi. Store data in-memory using Go maps and structs (no database required for this prototype). Define these structs: Employee (id, name, managerId, leaveBalances map[string]float64), LeaveRequest (id, employeeId, managerId, leaveType, startDate, endDate, reason, status, managerComments, submittedAt, reviewedAt). Initialize sample data: at least 5 employees with 2 managers, each employee has initial balances (annual: 20, sick: 10, personal: 5). Manager-employee relationships must be set via managerId field. Implement these endpoints: (1) GET /health returns {status: 'ok'}. (2) POST /api/leave-requests accepts JSON, validates fields, checks for overlapping requests (same employee, overlapping date range), verifies sufficient balance by calculating business days between dates and comparing to available balance, generates UUID for id, sets status to pending, captures submittedAt timestamp, deducts balance immediately (optimistic), returns 201 with created object or 400/409 on validation failure. (3) GET /api/leave-requests supports query params employeeId, managerId, status; if managerId is provided, return only requests from that manager's direct reports; if employeeId is provided, return that employee's requests; if status is provided, filter by status; return array of LeaveRequest objects. (4) POST /api/leave-requests/{id}/approve accepts managerId and optional comments, verifies the manager is the direct manager of the employee who submitted the request (403 if not), sets status to approved, captures reviewedAt timestamp, stores managerComments, returns updated LeaveRequest. (5) POST /api/leave-requests/{id}/reject accepts managerId and optional comments, verifies manager authorization same as approve, sets status to rejected, restores the deducted leave balance, captures reviewedAt, stores managerComments, returns updated LeaveRequest. (6) GET /api/employees/{id}/balance returns current balances by type for the employee. Use proper HTTP status codes. Enable CORS for frontend access. Use sync.RWMutex for thread-safe access to in-memory data. Parse dates in YYYY-MM-DD format. Calculate business days excluding weekends for balance deduction (simple heuristic: (endDate - startDate + 1) * 5/7). Log requests to stdout. Handle edge cases: invalid date ranges (end before start), non-existent employee or manager IDs (404), attempting to approve already approved/rejected requests (400). Return JSON errors with {error: 'message'} structure. Dockerfile: multi-stage build with golang:1.21 for build and alpine:latest for runtime, expose port 9090, set CMD to run the binary.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"sourceSpec\": \"spec-v1\"\n}","numLines":44,"startLine":1,"totalLines":44}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KU5xuEb9jg7MqYGsWvz61u","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of what I need to build. Let me analyze the design:\n\n1. **leave-web-app**: React + TypeScript + Vite SPA served on port 9090 (nginx)\n   - Routes: /login, /dashboard, /request, /history\n   - Communicates with leave-api via /api/*\n   - Multi-stage Docker build: Node.js + nginx\n   - workload.yaml with dependency on leave-api\n\nKey API endpoints on leave-api:\n\n\n- GET /health\n- POST /api/leave-requests\n- GET /api/leave-requests?employeeId=&managerId=&status=\n- POST /api/leave-requests/{id}/approve\n- POST /api/leave-requests/{id}/reject\n- GET /api/employees/{id}/balance\n\nI'm noticing a discrepancy in the port configuration. The component mentions port 3000, but ASDLC guidelines specify port 9090 for SPAs behind nginx. I'll go with 9090 as the nginx port and configure it to proxy /api/* requests to the leave-api service.\n\nNow I'm setting up the React frontend structure with the necessary configuration files for the project. Now I'm mapping out the file structure with TypeScript types, an authentication context, and pages for login, dashboard, leave requests, and history. The API will route through nginx on port 9090, proxying `/api/*` calls to the leave-api service while serving the SPA from the root path. For the workload configuration, I need to declare the dependency on leave-api so the services can communicate properly.\n\nI'm planning the tech stack with React, React Router, Material UI, and Vite, then I'll configure nginx to handle both the health check endpoint and the SPA routing pattern. Let me start building out all the implementation files now.\n\nDefining the TypeScript types...\n\nNow I'm working through the API client functions for fetching balances, querying leave requests, and handling approvals and rejections. I need to figure out the nginx proxy routing—the leave-api serves routes under `/api/`, so I should configure nginx to forward `/api/` requests to the backend's `/api/` path rather than stripping the prefix. I'm working through the nginx proxy_pass configuration to get the routing right—when location has no trailing slash and proxy_pass points to just the backend host without a path, nginx preserves the full request URI, so `/api/leave-requests` gets passed through as-is to the backend. This means I should configure it to proxy `/api` directly to the backend URL, which will then receive the complete path including `/api/leave-requests` as expected by the leave-api service.\n\nFor the frontend, I'm setting `BASE_URL` to `/api` so all API calls route through the nginx proxy, and the entrypoint script will inject this at runtime via `window.RUNTIME_BACKEND_API_URL`. I'm finishing up the API endpoint paths and now mapping out all the files I need to create for this frontend project, starting with configuration files like package.json and tsconfig, then moving through the React components, pages, and context setup. Writing nginx configuration... calls `BASE_URL + \"/leave-requests\"` which the browser sends to nginx, and nginx proxies it to the actual backend. So the frontend only needs to know about the `/api` path that nginx exposes, while the real backend URL stays hidden in the nginx configuration.\n\nFor local development, I can set `VITE_API_BASE_URL` to point directly to the backend or use Vite's proxy config to handle the routing.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out the full implementation. I'll structure the project with separate directories for components, context, and utilities, using Material-UI v5 for the UI.\n\nSetting up package.json with the necessary dependencies... Setting up the TypeScript configuration with strict type checking enabled, and configuring Vite to build the React application with the output going to the dist directory. Defining the core data structures for leave requests, including the request details, employee leave balances, and the payloads needed for creating and reviewing leave requests.\n\nNow I'm setting up the API module with a base URL that can be configured at runtime, and building a generic request function that handles authentication by redirecting to login if the user is unauthorized.\n\nDefining the API endpoints... Writing the auth context... Writing the Layout component... Writing the login form... Building the dashboard page... I'm setting up the review dialog state to track which request is being reviewed and what action to take, along with comment input and a reviewing flag. Then I'm creating a useEffect hook that redirects to login if there's no user, and loads either the employee's leave balance and recent requests or the manager's pending requests depending on their role.\n\nNow I'm implementing the review handler that processes either an approval or rejection, sends the appropriate request with the manager's ID and comments, then removes the processed request from the pending list and clears the review state. Building the employee dashboard layout... Building the request cards... Building the leave request cards... I'm setting up the request page component with form fields for leave type, dates, and reason, pulling in the necessary hooks and API functions to handle leave request creation.\n\nBuilding the component logic... Now I'm checking if there's enough leave balance available for the requested dates, and if so, submitting the leave request to create it. If the submission succeeds, I'll show a success message and redirect to the history page after a brief delay, otherwise I'll display the error that was returned.\n\nBuilding the form UI... Writing the form fields... Writing the HistoryPage component... Building the leave history interface... Writing the table structure... Setting up the routing structure with a catch-all route that redirects unmatched paths back to the dashboard, then wrapping everything in providers for theming, authentication, and browser routing. Finally, I'm rendering the app into the DOM with React's strict mode enabled, and configuring nginx to serve the application on port 9090. Setting up the runtime configuration file that exposes the API endpoint to the frontend, then executing the entrypoint command to start the nginx server.\n\nI'm creating a multi-stage Docker build that compiles the Vite app with the API base URL, copies the built files to an nginx container, and sets up the entrypoint script to dynamically inject the backend URL at runtime.\n\nNow I'm defining the workload configuration for Kubernetes that exposes the web app on port 9090 and binds the leave-api backend endpoint as an environment variable.\n\nI need to be careful about the TypeScript compiler settings—if strict mode is enabled with `noUnusedLocals` and `noUnusedParameters`, I might run into compilation errors when building, so I should keep that in mind. Simplifying the tsconfig.json configuration...\n\nNow I'm cleaning up unused imports like the `Divider` component from DashboardPage, and double-checking that MUI v5's Grid component will work properly in the Docker build environment—it should be fine as-is. I need to finalize the code and write all the files now. Let me also verify the nginx configuration for the API proxy - I want to make sure the routing works correctly when requests come through to the backend, particularly how the path gets handled with or without trailing slashes in the proxy_pass directive. Writing the configuration files...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4178,"cache_read_input_tokens":16090,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4178,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":31,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d7e8bf62-199f-4dd8-b4d4-7def9b222e46","u